  "Idea": "Latent Causal Inference for Annotation Diversity (LCI-AD) is a self-supervised framework that learns disentangled representations of annotator behavior by identifying invariant and variant components in labeling decisions without relying on predefined causal graphs or extensive annotator metadata. LCI-AD introduces a meta-causal learning architecture that models each annotator as a stochastic policy in a latent causal space, where decisions emerge from interactions between task-specific content factors and context-sensitive bias factors. The core innovation lies in the use of 'synthetic interventions'—data-augmented perturbations of input instances (e.g., gender-swapping names in text, color-inverting faces in images)—to simulate counterfactual scenarios and detect systematic deviations in annotator responses. These deviations are used to train a contrastive causal encoder that separates stable, content-driven agreement from unstable, context-dependent disagreement. A dual-regularization scheme is applied: (1) 'Interventional Consistency Loss' enforces that predictions should remain invariant under non-causal context shifts unless justified by content changes; and (2) 'Disagreement Entropy Regularization' preserves high-entropy outputs in cases where annotators diverge due to legitimate subjectivity (e.g., aesthetic judgment), while suppressing entropy when divergence stems from detectable bias patterns. The framework further includes a Causal Active Query Module (CAQM) that selects both new instances and new annotators based on maximal expected interventional discrepancy—i.e., those likely to reveal new causal pathways or break existing spurious correlations. This enables efficient exploration of the annotation manifold. Crucially, LCI-AD does not assume access to ground truth labels during training; instead, it bootstraps consensus through iterative refinement of causal invariance, making it ideal for early-stage data collection in sensitive domains lik