{
  "Idea": "Causal Adaptive Annotation Networks (CAAN) is a novel framework designed to collect, model, and leverage multi-annotator data in a way that preserves meaningful diversity while actively identifying and mitigating sources of systematic bias. At its core, CAAN uses Structural Causal Models (SCMs) to represent how latent factors—such as annotator expertise, demographic background, cultural context, and task ambiguity—influence labeling decisions. These SCMs are integrated into a neural architecture with two parallel pathways: a \u2018Content Path\u2019 that learns the underlying true label distribution, and a \u2018Bias Path\u2019 that models deviation patterns due to known and latent confounders. Using counterfactual regularization inspired by Pearl\u2019s do-calculus, CAAN estimates what each annotator would label an instance if certain bias-inducing factors were intervened upon (e.g., \u2018what would this annotator say if they had no exposure to stereotypical associations?\u2019). These counterfactual labels inform adaptive attention weights over annotators during training, down-weighting biased contributions while up-weighting those reflecting principled disagreement. Crucially, CAAN does not assume a single ground truth; instead, it clusters instances into \u2018ambiguity regimes\u2019 (clear-cut, subjectively ambiguous, systematically biased) and applies regime-specific aggregation rules. For example, in subjectively ambiguous cases (e.g., sentiment analysis of sarcasm), CAAN preserves diversity via ensemble distillation, whereas in biased cases (e.g., gender-stereotyped occupation labeling), it applies causal intervention to reconstruct de-biased consensus. An active annotation module further guides data collection by querying new annotators whose predicted causal profiles complement existing ones, maximizing coverage of diverse reasoning pathways. This makes CAAN particularly powerful in low-resource, high-stakes settings like medical diagnosis or fairness auditing, where both accuracy and representational fairness are paramount.",
